\begin{abstract}
Let $C$ and $C'$ be two smooth self transverse immersions of $S^1$
into ${\mathbb R}^2$. Both $C$ and $C'$ subdivide the plane into a number of disks and one
unbounded component. An isotopy of the plane which takes $C$ to $C'$ induces
a 1-1 correspondence between the disks of $C$ and $C'$. An obvious necessary
condition for there to exist an area-preserving isotopy of the plane
taking $C$ to $C'$ is that there exists an isotopy for which the area of every
disk of $C$ equals that of the corresponding disk of $C'$. In this paper
we show that this is also a sufficient condition.
\end{abstract}


